<item>
            <title>[LU-20188] MDS-OST synchronization improvements</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-20188</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;I&apos;d like to share few thoughs on MDS-OST the synchronization process we have now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As you know we use llog which is supposed to work like a circular buffer. There is a problem in the current implementation though. Originally the idea was that generic Lustre recovery takes care and a failed RPC would get through at some point or we just ignore an error as is, keep corresponding llog record and hope that a next reboot would re-process this lost record.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are few of problems with this approach:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;the llog can overflow before &#171;next&#187; reboot&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;lost (due to an RPC error) record leads to llog overflow at some point&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;re-processing old record may apply data outdated by another change long ago&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;So it&apos;s probably time to re-think how to deal with all this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Define transient errors (like EIO, EINVAL, what else?) and block processing new records
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;probably define how many retries are allowed, then drop RPC and record?&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Limit number of saved failed RPCs so they don&apos;t consume too much RAM&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Define &#171;good&#187; errors (like ENOENT) and just cancel llog records immediately&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;This way we&apos;re still able to hit llog overflow problem if processing is being blocked for long enough. The only workaround would be to drop the oldest records to keep going.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;comments, thoughts are welcome.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
